            "subject": "LU-9499 lfsck: set target bitmap properly"
          }
        ],
        "author": {
          "name": "Fan Yong",
          "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
          "date": "2017-08-08 20:27:32.000000000",
          "tz": 480
        },
        "committer": {
          "name": "Fan Yong",
          "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
          "date": "2017-08-08 21:37:15.000000000",
          "tz": 480
        },
        "subject": "LU-9410 ldiskfs: handle unmatched bitmap",
        "message": "LU-9410 ldiskfs: handle unmatched bitmap\n\nTwo fixes:\n\n1) Read bitmap with lock\nThe old logic will set the bitmap buffer head as 'bitmap_uptodate'\nbefore buffer head is really read from disk. If others also want\nto read such bitmap during such interval by race, then the latter\nmay get uninitialized bitmap, as to some fake data corruption.\n\nThis patch makes the bitmap reader to take lock on the bitmap buffer\nhead before checking whether it is up-to-date or not. Because the\nfirstly bitmap reader will hold such lock when loading the bitmap\nfrom disk, then it will prevent the others accessing uninitialized\nbitmap. It may be not the perfect solution, but we can use it to\nresolve our current trouble.\n\n2) Set free blocks count for non-initialized group\nldiskfs_init_block_bitmap() will initialize the group block bitmap,\nbut the free_blocks_count in the group descriptor maybe still zero.\nThat will cause the subsequent ldiskfs_mb_check_ondisk_bitmap() to\nreport corruption by wrong.\n\nThis patch sets the free_blocks_count in the group descriptor with\nthe real free blocks count in the group.\n\nSigned-off-by: Fan Yong <fan.yong@intel.com>\nChange-Id: I63f79eb671930743db31cf1c0c2724946b250777\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
    }
  },
